His last prayers were held at TSS mosque before his burial at Ganjoni Muslim Cemetery in Ganjoni area on Monday afternoon.





Mourners carry the remains of former Feisal FC and Harambee Stars striker, Ali Kajo, who died on December 28, 2020 while receiving treatment at Sayidna Fatma Hospital in Mombasa.
Photo credit: Abdulrahman Sheriff | Nation Media Group


Messages of condolences have been received from fans in various parts of Coast region expressing their sorrow over his death.
Most of the fans blamed Coast leaders, Mombasa County and national government for failing to ensure Kajo lived a decent life despite dedicating his youthful years to the national team which he helped win many regional titles. 





Former Feisal FC manager Abdullahi Bashasha urged Mombasa County government to name one of the city's streets after Kajo as a way of honouring him.
"Ali Kajo deserves to be honoured for the way he served this nation. I would recommend one of the streets of Mombasa be named after him in recognition of his contribution to Mombasa, Coast and Kenya football,” said Bashasha.
He is survived by a widow, 12 children and several grandchildren.  Jubilee and ODM clear prospective candidates to contest party primaries for Nairobi gubernatorial by-elections. What apparently infuriated the ANC boss was what appeared to be an ultimatum for him and Mr Wetang'ula. Exiled lawyer gets direct nomination from the Thirdway Alliance Kenya party to run in the forthcoming mini-poll.